    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "ok that makes sense. so it's basically just a way to make sure nobody gets scammed? i'm just a bit nervous about where all that money is sitting in the meantime. who actually controls the money while it's in there? like, can the seller just grab it if they want to?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Think of escrow as a highly regulated safety net, designed specifically to prevent exactly the kind of scamming you're worried about. The escrow agent is a neutral third party, not you or the seller, and they are legally bound to follow strict rules. They can only release the funds to the seller *after* all agreed-upon conditions—like a satisfactory inspection and clear title—have been met, and *then* they release the final proceeds to you.\n\nThe seller cannot just grab the money; the funds are locked until the closing documents are finalized and approved by the relevant parties. This process is designed to be transparent and secure.",
